sentences.content: These pronouns are used to form the subject of a sentence or as a predicate noun (aka predicate nominative) when following a form of be verb (e.g., is, was) and it renames or describes the subject of the sentence.
Subjective pronouns include: I, you, he, she, it, we, they.

sentences.content: Objective pronouns are used as direct objects, indirect objects or objects of the preposition.
Objective pronouns include: me, you, him, her, it, us, them.
Possessive pronouns are used to indicate ownership of objects.
Possessive pronouns include: my, your, his, hers, its, our, ours, their, theirs.
